0:10:56.26,000 --> 0:10:58,000
was segregated and wouldn't have her.

261
0:10:58.26,000 --> 0:11:01,000
We don't hear about the Einstein who used his celebrity

262
0:11:01.26,000 --> 0:11:04,000
to advocate for political prisoners in Europe

263
0:11:04.26,000 --> 0:11:06,000
or the Scottsboro boys

264
0:11:06.26,000 --> 0:11:08,000
in the American South.

265
0:11:08.26,000 --> 0:11:11,000
Einstein believed deeply

266
0:11:11.26,000 --> 0:11:13,000
that science should transcend

267
0:11:13.26,000 --> 0:11:15,000
national and ethnic divisions.

268
0:11:15.26,000 --> 0:11:18,000
But he watched physicists and chemists

269
0:11:18.26,000 --> 0:11:21,000
become the purveyors of weapons of mass destruction

270
0:11:21.26,000 --> 0:11:23,000
in the early 20th century.

271
0:11:23.26,000 --> 0:11:26,000
He once said that science in his generation

272
0:11:26.26,000 --> 0:11:28,000
had become like a razor blade

273
0:11:28.26,000 --> 0:11:3,000
in the hands of a three-year-old.

274
0:11:30.26,000 --> 0:11:32,000
And Einstein foresaw

275
0:11:32.26,000 --> 0:11:34,000
that as we grow more modern

276
0:11:34.26,000 --> 0:11:36,000
and technologically advanced,

277
0:11:36.26,000 --> 0:11:38,000
we need the virtues

278
0:11:38.26,000 --> 0:11:41,000
our traditions carry forward in time

279
0:11:41.26,000 --> 0:11:43,000
more, not less.

280
0:11:43.26,000 --> 0:11:47,000
He liked to talk about the spiritual geniuses of the ages.

281
0:11:47.26,000 --> 0:11:49,000
Some of his favorites were Moses,

282
0:11:49.26,000 --> 0:11:52,000
Jesus, Buddha, St. Francis of Assisi,

283
0:11:52.26,000 --> 0:11:55,000
Gandhi -- he adored his contemporary, Gandhi.

284
0:11:55.26,000 --> 0:11:57,000
And Einstein said --

285
0:11:57.26,000 --> 0:11:59,000
and I think this is a quote,

286
0:11:59.26,000 --> 0:12:01,000
again, that has not been passed down in his legacy --

287
0:12:01.26,000 --> 0:12:03,000
that "these kinds of people

288
0:12:03.26,000 --> 0:12:05,000
are geniuses in the art of living,

289
0:12:05.26,000 --> 0:12:07,000
more necessary

290
0:12:07.26,000 --> 0:12:1,000
to the dignity, security and joy of humanity

291
0:12:10.26,000 --> 0:12:13,000
than the discoverers of objective knowledge."

292
0:12:15.26,000 --> 0:12:17,000
Now invoking Einstein

293
0:12:17.26,000 --> 0:12:2,000
might not seem the best way to bring compassion down to earth

294
0:12:20.26,000 --> 0:12:22,000
and make it seem accessible to all the rest of us,

295
0:12:22.26,000 --> 0:12:25,000
but actually it is.

296
0:12:25.26,000 --> 0:12:27,000
I want to show you

297
0:12:27.26,000 --> 0:12:3,000
the rest of this photograph,

298
0:12:30.26,000 --> 0:12:32,000
because this photograph

299
0:12:32.26,000 --> 0:12:35,000
is analogous to what we do to the word "compassion" in our culture --

300
0:12:35.26,000 --> 0:12:37,000
we clean it up

301
0:12:37.26,000 --> 0:12:4,000
and we diminish its depths and its grounding

302
0:12:40.26,000 --> 0:12:42,000
in life, which is messy.

303
0:12:42.26,000 --> 0:12:44,000
So in this photograph

304
0:12:44.26,000 --> 0:12:46,000
you see a mind looking out a window

305
0:12:46.26,000 --> 0:12:48,000
at what might be a cathedral -- it's not.

306
0:12:48.26,000 --> 0:12:5,000
This is the full photograph,

307
0:12:50.26,000 --> 0:12:52,000
and you see a middle-aged man wearing a leather jacket,

308
0:12:52.26,000 --> 0:12:54,000
smoking a cigar.

309
0:12:54.26,000 --> 0:12:56,000
And by the look of that paunch,

310
0:12:56.26,000 --> 0:12:58,000
he hasn't been doing enough yoga.

311
0:12:58.26,000 --> 0:13:01,000
We put these two photographs side-by-side on our website,

312
0:13:01.26,000 --> 0:13:03,000
and someone said, "When I look at the first photo,

313
0:13:03.26,000 --> 0:13:05,000
I ask myself, what was he thinking?

314
0:13:05.26,000 --> 0:13:07,000
And when I look at the second, I ask,

315
0:13:07.26,000 --> 0:13:1,000
what kind of person was he? What kind of man is this?"

316
0:13:10.26,000 --> 0:13:12,000
Well, he was complicated.

317
0:13:12.26,000 --> 0:13:14,000
He was incredibly compassionate

318
0:13:14.26,000 --> 0:13:16,000
in some of his relationships

319
0:13:16.26,000 --> 0:13:19,000
and terribly inadequate in others.

320
0:13:19.26,000 --> 0:13:22,000
And it is much harder, often,

321
0:13:22.26,000 --> 0:13:26,000
to be compassionate towards those closest to us,

322
0:13:26.26,000 --> 0:13:29,000
which is another quality in the universe of compassion,

323
0:13:29.26,000 --> 0:13:31,000
on its dark side,

324
0:13:31.26,000 --> 0:13:34,000
that also deserves our serious attention and illumination.

325
0:13:36.26,000 --> 0:13:39,000
Gandhi, too, was a real flawed human being.

326
0:13:39.26,000 --> 0:13:42,000
So was Martin Luther King, Jr. So was Dorothy Day.

327
0:13:42.26,000 --> 0:13:44,000
So was Mother Teresa.

328
0:13:44.26,000 --> 0:13:46,000
So are we all.

329
0:13:46.26,000 --> 0:13:48,000
And I want to say

330
0:13:48.26,000 --> 0:13:5,000
that it is a liberating thing

331
0:13:50.26,000 --> 0:13:52,000
to realize that that is no obstacle to compassion --

332
0:13:52.26,000 --> 0:13:55,000
following on what Fred Luskin says --

333
0:13:55.26,000 --> 0:13:58,000
that these flaws just make us human.

334
0:13:58.26,000 --> 0:14:01,000
Our culture is obsessed with perfection

335
0:14:01.26,000 --> 0:14:03,000
and with hiding problems.

336
0:14:03.26,000 --> 0:14:05,000
But what a liberating thing to realize

337
0:14:05.26,000 --> 0:14:07,000
that our problems, in fact,

338
0:14:07.26,000 --> 0:14:1,000
are probably our richest sources

339
0:14:10.26,000 --> 0:14:14,000
for rising to this ultimate virtue of compassion,

340
0:14:14.26,000 --> 0:14:16,000
towards bringing compassion

341
0:14:16.26,000 --> 0:14:19,000
towards the suffering and joys of others.

342
0:14:20.26,000 --> 0:14:23,000
Rachel Naomi Remen is a better doctor

343
0:14:23.26,000 --> 0:14:25,000
because of her life-long struggle with Crohn's disease.

344
0:14:25.26,000 --> 0:14:27,000
Einstein became a humanitarian,

345
0:14:27.26,000 --> 0:14:29,000
not because of his exquisite knowledge

346
0:14:29.26,000 --> 0:14:31,000
of space and time and matter,

347
0:14:31.26,000 --> 0:14:34,000
but because he was a Jew as Germany grew fascist.

348
0:14:34.26,000 --> 0:14:37,000
And Karen Armstrong, I think you would also say

349
0:14:37.26,000 --> 0:14:4,000
that it was some of your very wounding experiences

350
0:14:40.26,000 --> 0:14:42,000
in a religious life that,

351
0:14:42.26,000 --> 0:14:44,000
with a zigzag,

352
0:14:44.26,000 --> 0:14:47,000
have led to the Charter for Compassion.

353
0:14:48.26,000 --> 0:14:51,000
Compassion can't be reduced to sainthood

354
0:14:51.26,000 --> 0:14:54,000
any more than it can be reduced to pity.

355
0:14:55.26,000 --> 0:14:57,000
So I want to propose

356
0:14:57.26,000 --> 0:15:,000
a final definition of compassion --

357
0:15:00.26,000 --> 0:15:03,000
this is Einstein with Paul Robeson by the way --

358
0:15:03.26,000 --> 0:15:05,000
and that would be for us

359
0:15:05.26,000 --> 0:15:08,000
to call compassion a spiritual technology.

360
0:15:09.26,000 --> 0:15:11,000
Now our traditions contain

361
0:15:11.26,000 --> 0:15:13,000
vast wisdom about this,

362
0:15:13.26,000 --> 0:15:16,000
and we need them to mine it for us now.

363
0:15:16.26,000 --> 0:15:19,000
But compassion is also equally at home

364
0:15:19.26,000 --> 0:15:22,000
in the secular as in the religious.

365
0:15:22.26,000 --> 0:15:25,000
So I will paraphrase Einstein in closing

366
0:15:25.26,000 --> 0:15:27,000
and say that humanity,

367
0:15:27.26,000 --> 0:15:29,000
the future of humanity,

368
0:15:29.26,000 --> 0:15:31,000
needs this technology

369
0:15:31.26,000 --> 0:15:33,000
as much as it needs all the others

370
0:15:33.26,000 --> 0:15:36,000
that have now connected us

371
0:15:36.26,000 --> 0:15:38,000
and set before us

372
0:15:38.26,000 --> 0:15:4,000
the terrifying and wondrous possibility

373
0:15:40.26,000 --> 0:15:43,000
of actually becoming one human race.

374
0:15:43.26,000 --> 0:15:45,000
Thank you.

375
0:15:45.26,000 --> 0:15:47,000
(Applause)

